Homo sapiens then either developed the 
technology themselves, or learned it from Homo heidelbergensis, which 
helped them to move out of Africa and out-compete Neanderthals.

Researchers are now studying the stone javelin tips, recently found at an Ethiopian Stone Age site known as Gademotta.

The Gademotta Formation in the Main Ethiopian Rift Valley was discovered in the 1970s and is best known for its Middle Stone Age archaeological sites.

Scientists the University of California at Berkeley’s Human Evolution Research Center were recently able to study the spears and determine their age.

